listitem:\n      - link \"Acknowledgements\" :\n        - /url: \"#acknowledgements\"\n  - banner:\n    - heading \"LangGraph 
overview\"  \n    - button \"Copy page\" :\n      - text: Copy page\n    - button \"More actions\" :\n  - text: Trusted by 
companies shaping the future of agents— including Klarna, Uber, J.P. Morgan, and more— LangGraph is a low-level orchestration 
framework and runtime for building, managing, and deploying long-running, stateful agents. LangGraph is very low-level, and 
focused entirely on agent\n  - strong: orchestration\n  - text: . Before using LangGraph, we recommend you familiarize yourself
with some of the components used to build agents, starting with\n  - link \"models\" :\n    - /url: 
/oss/python/langchain/models\n  - text: and\n  - link \"tools\" :\n    - /url: /oss/python/langchain/tools\n  - text: . We will
commonly use\n  - link \"LangChain\"  :\n    - /url: /oss/python/langchain/overview\n  - text: components throughout the 
documentation to integrate models and tools, but you don’t need to use LangChain to use LangGraph. If you are just getting 
started with agents or want a higher-level abstraction, we recommend you use LangChain’s\n  - link \"agents\" :\n    - /url: 
/oss/python/langchain/agents\n  - text: \"that provide prebuilt architectures for common LLM and tool-calling loops. LangGraph 
is focused on the underlying capabilities important for agent orchestration: durable execution, streaming, human-in-the-loop, 
and more.\"\n  - heading \"Navigate to header Install\"  :\n    - link \"Navigate to header\" :\n      - /url: \"#install\"\n  
- text: Install\n    - tab \"pip\"  \n    - tab \"uv\" \n  - button \"Copy the contents from the code block\" :\n    - code: 
